The main issue is the transference of certain populations, which in Soviet times were the basis of the regional political elite, to other countries, for example, to Russia, Kazakhstan and Turkey. All this, coupled with great demographic losses undoubtedly had a negative effect on the balanced employment of the population, the pace of industrialization of the provinces and the restoration of the infrastructure in cities and rural areas.
So, the overall socio-economic problems of Uzbekistan are the following:
► breach of the social justice (e.g. East Uzbekistan) because of the different economic development rate;
► a punitive character of the child welfare » because of the great child labor rate (the poorest sections of the population)
► high rate of unemployment and open registration of > huge segments of the working population. Thanks to the special reservation quotas in some segments of the service and lending fields - seven times more people are employed than are needed (Solovyev, 1993; Umarov, 1993).
Thus we can see several hot points in social problems of Uzbekistan, including the political crisis and the gap between the East and the West of Uzbekistan, there is theoretical and practical problem of the significance of the regional approach and advances of the local development in theories.
